despo1ler, it is true that VLC is good for checking films this way. However it does not always work, i'd say 75% of the time it's good. 

Some films (for some odd reason, anyone technical can explain it?) require you to download it all first before playing properly.

VLC will work where the movie file format does NOT have the "index" at the end of the file.  AVI has index info all the way through it, so VLC can reconstruct the index when "repairing".  Other formats have the index at the end - like WMV - so you have to download the lot before you can play it.
